# frustum_look_down.tas — Cone-cull regression for "looking straight down".
#
# Purpose: pitch the camera as far down as the clamp allows (≈ -89°) on a
# flatland world, then dump a frame. The dumped frame must NOT be black —
# the chunk the player is standing in (and its neighbours) must remain
# visible regardless of how aggressive the cone-cull setting is.
#
# Why this exists: cone culling against a chunk bounding sphere only works
# correctly if the camera-inside-bounding-sphere short-circuit fires. If the
# short-circuit is broken, looking straight down at narrow fov drops every
# chunk centre behind the camera and the screen goes pure sky. The 3×3
# camera-neighbourhood safety net in `frustum.zig::keepChunk` is the second
# line of defence — between the two, looking-straight-down on flatland
# should always produce a frame whose mean RGB sits well clear of black.
#
# Tick rate: 120 Hz. Pitch sensitivity is 0.002 rad/px, starting pitch is
# -0.3 rad. The voxel demo inverts mouse-Y in main.zig before forwarding to
# camera.rotate, so a POSITIVE dy in this TAS pulls the pitch DOWN. A
# +700 dy mouse_move drives pitch into the clamp at -π/2 + 0.01 (the
# camera's hard lower limit), so this script does NOT depend on exact
# pitch values — only on "fully looking down".
#
# Usage (from utils/swindowzig):
#
#   zig build native -Dexample=voxel
#
#   # Baseline — frustum off, must produce a non-black ground.
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --world=flatland --aa=none \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/frustum_look_down.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/frustum_look_down_none.ppm
#
#   # Aggressive cone — must STILL produce a non-black ground because the
#   # 3×3 safety net + camera-inside-bounding-sphere shortcut both fire.
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --world=flatland --aa=none \
#     --frustum=cone --frustum-fov-deg=30 \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/frustum_look_down.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/frustum_look_down_cone30.ppm
#
# Verification: parse the PPM P6 header, then average the body bytes.
# A reference one-liner (Python) is:
#
#   python3 -c '
#   import sys
#   p = open(sys.argv[1], "rb").read()
#   nl1 = p.index(b"\n"); nl2 = p.index(b"\n", nl1+1); nl3 = p.index(b"\n", nl2+1)
#   body = p[nl3+1:]
#   print(sum(body) / len(body))
#   ' /tmp/frustum_look_down_cone30.ppm
#
# Pass criterion: mean byte value > 5 (true black ≈ 0; the flatland grass
# top under the default sky reads ~30–60 per channel even after the painter's
# sort, so anything above ~5 confirms terrain is visible).
#
# Tick numbering is relative to the first post-loading tick.

# --- Capture mouse ---
1 mouse_down left
2 mouse_up left

# --- Pitch all the way down. +700 dy at 0.002 rad/px (with the inversion
#     applied in main.zig) = -1.4 rad delta on pitch; the camera's clamp at
#     -π/2 + 0.01 catches it. Starting pitch is -0.3 so this puts us flush
#     against the lower clamp. ---
3 mouse_move 0 700

# --- Hold steady for several ticks so any pending mesh upload completes
#     before --dump-frame snapshots the surface. ---
5 mouse_move 0 0
10 mouse_move 0 0
15 mouse_move 0 0
20 mouse_move 0 0
